{"source_key":"sha256-f88bd5c54ac5fbbfc982c6d403b2565f","record_index":640,"record_hash":"sha256:852b7388c79fcb4aa6e2692b4c5b68ac01697554bfc63ae23562c8ff9851a037","timestamp":"2026-05-24T15:05:09.906Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 156895\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 2808\nOutput:\n  `but-agentlog` read/projection crate if the full GitButler workspace\n  dependency graph is too heavy\n\nExample shape:\n\n```toml\nbut-agentlog = { git = \"https://github.com/gitbutlerapp/gitbutler.git\", rev = \"<pinned-revision>\", package = \"but-agentlog\" }\n```\n\nThe important rule is no copied reader logic. Forge may own Agent Trail\npublication and UI policy, but the canonical storage interpretation should stay\nin `but-agentlog`.\n\nBuild may start for public repos and publicly fetchable metadata. Private repo,\nteam, explicit-share, and richer publication flows are later work.\n\n## Server-Side Metadata Fetch\n\nFor public v1, the Forge server should be able to create an Agent Trail snapshot\non demand by fetching GitMeta metadata for the repository referenced by the PR\nURL.\n\nExample local setup:\n\n```ini\n[remote \"meta\"]\n  url = git@github.com:gitbutlerapp/gitbutler.git\n  fetch = +refs/meta/main:refs/meta/remote/main\n  meta = true\n  promisor = true\n  partialclonefilter = blob:none\n```\n\nThe server should not assume it can see a developer's local Git remote config.\nGiven a URL like:\n\n```text\nhttps://github.com/gitbutlerapp/gitbutler/pull/13936\n```\n\nthe server should resolve the public GitHub repository, then fetch\n`refs/meta/main` from that same public repository.\n\nPossible first flow:\n\n1. parse the PR URL into forge, owner, repo, and PR number\n2. fetch GitHub PR metadata and verify that the repository and pull request are\n   public/readable\n3. reject fork pull requests for v1\n4. create or refresh a server-side bare/cache checkout for the repository\n5. fetch `refs/meta/main`\n6. resolve the fetched metadata ref to an OID\n7. run `but-agentlog` lookup/projection code against\n   the fetched repository metadata\n8. generate a review-safe Agent Trail snapshot\n9. cache or return that snapshot according to the retention policy\n\nThe server can lazy-initialize repository storage. On the first request for a\nrepository, initializ\n[TRUNCATED]\nasy to scan\n- let the user expand exact transcript records when they need evidence\n- preserve chronological order without forcing the user to read every record\n\nThe reviewer should be able to answer:\n\n- what did the human ask?\n- what did the agent claim it did?\n- what files or areas did it touch or inspect?\n- what commands/tools ran?\n- what validation passed, failed, or was skipped?\n- what decisions, doubts, or follow-ups appeared during the work?\n\nThe UI should support both broad scanning and exact drill-down. A reviewer\nshould be able to start at the PR overview, jump into a highlighted turn, expand\nthe relevant tool call or assistant claim, then return to the overview without\nlosing context.\n\nRaw transcript records should remain available, but they should be treated as an\nevidence drawer, not the primary browsing mode.\n\n## Ranking And Highlighting\n\nThe page should rank or highlight likely relevant turns. Relevance is a product\ndecision above `but-agentlog`.\n\nGood signals:\n\n- direct review target observation\n- direct branch target observation\n- capture time near commits or PR updates\n- prompts mentioning the feature, bug, branch, or files\n- assistant claims about implementation or tests\n- tool calls that run tests, builds, formatters, or linters\n- later path or commit evidence, if added\n\nWeak signals:\n\n- backfilled turns with only capture-time environment snapshots\n- broad sessions that span unrelated work\n- sidecar review sessions that discuss the branch but did not implement it\n- turns related only through current branch state\n\nThe UI should expose why a turn is highlighted. Reviewers should not have to\nguess why a session appears.\n\n## Privacy And Publication\n\nAgent Trail is more sensitive than local handoff because it is meant to be\nopened by colleagues.\n\nFor public v1, Agent Trail treats a publicly fetchable `refs/meta/main` as\nalready published metadata. On-demand URL replacement does not grant access to\nprivate data; it only renders a review page from metadata that is fetchable\nwithout credentials.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T15:05:09.906Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}